The indicative is used with ‘ sunt,’ or ‘ est qui,' when par- ticular persons are alluded to, as here the Greeks in opposition to the Romans. So Epp. ii. 2. 182: “ Argentum—sunt qui 11011 habeant, est qui non curat habere,’' where by the latter is distinctly indicated the wise man. This distinction may be observed, more or less evidently, in every passage of Horace, where the words occur (see Index, ‘ qui ³), unless ‘ est qui ' below (v. 19) be an exception. It is not impossible, that there he may mean an allusion to some particular person in a good-humoured way.
